      "id": 10,
      "options": {
        "content": "## Alert Classifications\n\n| Classification | Risk | Action |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Web Application Attack** | \ud83d\udd34 High | External probe/exploit attempt. Check source IP in the attacks table \u2192 block persistent offenders in AdGuard or router firewall. |\n| **Misc Attack** | \ud83d\udfe0 Medium | Targeted attack pattern. Review source IP \u2014 if external and repeated, block it. |\n| **Attempted Denial of Service** | \ud83d\udfe1 Low (internal) | Usually your server doing UPnP/SSDP to the router. Suppressed going forward. If external source, investigate. |\n| **Generic Protocol Command Decode** | \ud83d\udfe1 Low | HTTP protocol anomalies. Usually benign \u2014 check destination if unfamiliar. |\n| **Device Retrieving External IP Address** | \u26aa Info | Something checked its public IP. Normal for Docker containers. |\n| **Potential Corporate Privacy Violation** | \u26aa Info | BitTorrent (Transmission). Suppressed going forward. |\n| **Misc activity** | \u26aa Info | DNS over HTTPS, Go clients, etc. All suppressed going forward. |\n| **Not Suspicious Traffic** | \u26aa Info | APT package manager. Suppressed. |\n\n> **Priority 1** alerts after suppression = genuinely suspicious. Investigate immediately.  \n> **Priority 2** alerts = elevated concern, review within the day.\n",
        "mode": "markdown"
      },
      "title": "Alert Classification Guide \u2014 What to Investigate",
      "type": "text"
